{
  "doc_id": "41473",
  "text": "Coping capacity and coping behaviours were suggested to be closely correlated with noise annoyance and noise-associated health risks [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Pennig and Schady [CITATION_3] particularly suggested that a higher coping capacity decreased the level of annoyance. In addition, Kroesen, Molin and van Wee [CITATION_4] found negative attitudes to a noise source adversely affected coping capacity. However, these various non-acoustic factors have not been applied to the issue of building noises including floor impact noise.",
